      "writtenOn": "2026-06-10T20:55:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t think it\u0027s a good idea to use the word \"parent\" here. We already use it for two distinct concepts:\n1. Every git commit (other than the root) in a conversation repository has one or more parent commits. This is what the `parents` field in the `ConversationCommit` struct refers to.\n2. Every swarm message (other than the initial one) has a \"linearized parent\", which refers to the message that precedes it when the daemon sorts the messages in a conversation. This is stored in the `linearized_parent` field of `ConversationCommit` and in the `linearizedParent` field of `SwarmMessage`.\n\n(The two concepts are genuinely different: not every git commit corresponds to a swarm message, so not every git commit has a linearized parent. Moreover, the linearized parent of a swarm message may not be a git parent of the underlying commit.)\n\nFor this particular comment, you can just write \"affected message\". In general, you can use \"original message\" or \"edited message\" if you need to refer to the message targeted by an edition.",
      "range": {
